WEBVTT

00:01.393 --> 00:04.578
♪<i> It seems today</i>
<i> that all you see</i> ♪

00:04.730 --> 00:07.655
♪<i> Is violence in movies</i>
<i> and sex on TV</i> ♪

00:07.750 --> 00:11.343
♪<i> But where are those</i>
<i> good old-fashioned values</i> ♪

00:11.420 --> 00:14.404
♪<i> On which we used to rely?</i> ♪

00:14.423 --> 00:17.758
♪<i> Lucky there's a family guy</i> ♪

00:17.910 --> 00:21.411
♪<i> Lucky there's a man</i>
<i> who positively can do</i> ♪

00:21.430 --> 00:22.913
♪<i> All the things that make us</i> ♪

00:22.931 --> 00:24.172
♪<i> Laugh and cry</i> ♪

00:24.266 --> 00:30.070
♪<i> He's... a...</i>
<i> Fam... ily... Guy!</i> ♪

00:30.923 --> 00:32.589
Hi, I'm Peter Griffin.

00:32.682 --> 00:34.258
It's almost Oscar night.

00:34.276 --> 00:36.760
Boy, we've lost so many greats
this year,

00:36.853 --> 00:38.686
including
a dead costume designer

00:38.706 --> 00:40.188
who will get spill-over applause

00:40.282 --> 00:43.267
from the photo of Sean Connery
that directly precedes him.

00:43.285 --> 00:46.119
Tonight, we salute
some past Best Picture winners,

00:46.272 --> 00:48.589
whichever ones I spin
on this wheel.

00:54.538 --> 00:56.129
The wheel has spoken!

00:56.282 --> 00:57.798
<i> The Silence of the Lambs.</i>

00:57.966 --> 01:00.184
♪ ♪

01:04.381 --> 01:08.049
Ah... what a beautiful day
to not get bodily fluids

01:08.069 --> 01:10.069
thrown in your face and hair.

01:10.220 --> 01:14.389
And now, for some rock tunes
to pump me up.

01:14.408 --> 01:16.800
♪<i> One, two princes kneel</i>
<i> before you...</i> ♪

01:16.893 --> 01:19.986
Oh, right,
'cause it's the early '90s.

01:20.081 --> 01:21.988
Vaulting over a log.

01:22.141 --> 01:23.807
Jumping a water hazard.

01:23.900 --> 01:25.918
Climbing up a cargo net.

01:26.111 --> 01:27.920
Becoming an FBI agent
is basically

01:28.089 --> 01:30.497
like being on
<i> Battle of the Network Stars.</i>

01:30.649 --> 01:33.333
-♪<i> You rockets ain't in...</i> ♪
-(music stops)

01:33.427 --> 01:35.427
♪ ♪

01:38.081 --> 01:40.006
-Aah!
-Agent Starling.

01:40.101 --> 01:41.249
Good to see you.

01:41.327 --> 01:43.176
Wh-Why is your face so big?

01:43.329 --> 01:45.587
Oh, this movie is mostly
extreme close-ups.

01:45.606 --> 01:47.439
Oh. Yeah. Weird.

01:47.591 --> 01:49.333
Anyway, sorry you had to
come so quickly,

01:49.426 --> 01:51.835
but this thing
with no timetable couldn't wait.

01:51.854 --> 01:54.838
We need you to talk to
a super smart psychopath.

01:54.931 --> 01:56.173
How smart?

01:56.266 --> 01:57.765
Like, he can do
the<i> New York Times</i> crossword

01:57.860 --> 01:58.817
through Thursday.

01:59.044 --> 02:01.011
Friday, he can maybe get
a corner or two.

02:01.104 --> 02:02.770
So, what's the job?

02:02.790 --> 02:04.272
Fancy creep, eats people.

02:04.291 --> 02:06.183
-Talk to him.
-Got it.

02:06.201 --> 02:08.034
And this is a big deal,
'cause you're a woman.

02:08.129 --> 02:09.611
We're not gonna say
it's a big deal,

02:09.630 --> 02:12.113
but everyone watching
will know it's a big deal

02:12.133 --> 02:13.281
'cause of the time period,

02:13.300 --> 02:15.025
even though
a man is helping you.

02:15.043 --> 02:16.510
Now run along, toots.

02:17.471 --> 02:19.513
(bird cawing)

02:20.474 --> 02:21.974
(yelling gibberish)

02:22.201 --> 02:23.809
So, you're in the FBI, huh?

02:24.036 --> 02:25.719
Me, too.

02:25.813 --> 02:28.272
Got this bad boy
in Venice Beach.

02:29.799 --> 02:31.633
Okay, all right.

02:31.727 --> 02:33.318
You can talk to Lecter now.

02:33.470 --> 02:36.280
♪ ♪

02:40.143 --> 02:41.994
Hello, Clarice.

02:42.145 --> 02:44.479
Dr. Lecter, I need your help.

02:44.498 --> 02:47.574
Nope, nope, nope. I'll only help
if there's a quid pro quo.

02:47.726 --> 02:49.334
(sighs) Okay, what is it?

02:49.486 --> 02:53.563
I want Mario Lopez to record
my outgoing voice mail message.

02:53.582 --> 02:55.232
What?! You're insane!

02:55.325 --> 02:58.343
He's a huge star
at this specific sliver of time.

02:58.570 --> 03:01.405
Figure it out.
Those are my terms.

03:01.423 --> 03:03.390
♪ ♪

03:04.668 --> 03:06.018
(gasps)

03:06.245 --> 03:10.096
Sorry, these Capri Suns are
notoriously difficult to open.

03:10.191 --> 03:12.098
(Spin Doctors' "Two Princes"
playing on radio)

03:12.193 --> 03:15.402
♪<i> Yeah, one, two...</i> ♪

03:16.530 --> 03:18.363
(faintly):
♪<i> That's what I said now</i> ♪

03:18.590 --> 03:20.157
-♪<i> Princes...</i> ♪
-(music stops)

03:24.538 --> 03:26.205
(straining)

03:27.099 --> 03:28.432
You need some help?

03:28.525 --> 03:29.616
Yeah, thanks.

03:29.768 --> 03:33.069
I can't seem to get
this giant 1991 computer

03:33.121 --> 03:35.121
into the back of my van.

03:35.216 --> 03:39.292
Careful, I had it on for
20 minutes, so it's very hot.

03:39.445 --> 03:40.552
(grunts)

03:44.374 --> 03:46.541
Okay, I got what you asked for.

03:46.635 --> 03:48.285
<i> MARIO LOPEZ:</i>
<i> Hey, this is Mario Lopez</i>

03:48.378 --> 03:49.970
<i> letting you know</i>
<i> that Hannibal Lecter</i>

03:50.064 --> 03:51.288
<i> can't get to the phone</i>
<i> right now,</i>

03:51.306 --> 03:52.731
<i> so please leave a message.</i>

03:52.808 --> 03:54.733
<i> And now, I think I'm about</i>
<i> to be saved by the...</i>

03:54.960 --> 03:55.883
(beeps)

03:55.903 --> 03:56.977
Not good enough!

03:57.071 --> 03:58.904
I wanted him to record it
as Slater.

03:59.055 --> 04:00.906
What?! You never said that!

04:01.133 --> 04:02.724
It should've been understood.

04:02.743 --> 04:04.243
Don't test me, Starling.

04:04.394 --> 04:06.152
A census taker did that once,

04:06.247 --> 04:08.580
and I ate his liver
with dry Cheerios

04:08.732 --> 04:10.582
and a mashed-up banana.

04:10.692 --> 04:12.400
(slurping)

04:12.419 --> 04:14.920
Sorry, I'm just
a little nervous.

04:15.071 --> 04:16.496
When I was a girl,

04:16.648 --> 04:18.114
I went to live
on my uncle's farm,

04:18.166 --> 04:21.242
and I heard
these lambs screaming,

04:21.262 --> 04:22.928
screaming as they were
being slaughtered.

04:23.155 --> 04:24.671
It was horrible.

04:24.765 --> 04:27.582
-(applause)
-And I want to thank
Alan Weiss at William Morris.

04:27.676 --> 04:30.660
Also, my high school
drama teacher, Lucas Wohl.

04:30.754 --> 04:33.346
-(orchestral music plays)
-Oh, they were just killing
those poor lambs.

04:33.499 --> 04:34.681
I wanted to save them,
but I couldn't.

04:34.833 --> 04:37.759
And, Mandy and Jenny at home,
go to bed, kids.

04:37.778 --> 04:39.352
Mommy did it!

04:39.446 --> 04:41.671
I am coming home
with one of these!

04:41.765 --> 04:43.782
-(laughing)
-(applause)

04:44.009 --> 04:47.119
♪ ♪

04:50.607 --> 04:52.940
CVS brand lotion?

04:53.035 --> 04:55.460
It's the same ingredients
as Nivea.

04:56.538 --> 04:59.781
It puts the off-brand lotion
on its skin,

04:59.875 --> 05:02.208
or else it gets the hose again.

05:02.361 --> 05:03.969
The top isn't even a pump.

05:04.196 --> 05:06.379
You're paying for the pump!

05:06.532 --> 05:09.182
♪ ♪

05:13.372 --> 05:15.147
Dr. Lecter,
we are running out of time.

05:15.298 --> 05:17.131
I need you to give me some clue,

05:17.225 --> 05:19.526
anything that might lead me
in the right direction.

05:19.636 --> 05:22.487
(sighs) His name's Buffalo Bill,
heavyset blond kid

05:22.564 --> 05:25.382
who lives in that crappy place
behind McDonald's.

05:25.400 --> 05:26.641
Hmm.

05:26.660 --> 05:27.826
I'll have to really lean

05:28.053 --> 05:29.886
on my budding criminology skills

05:29.979 --> 05:32.572
to decipher
these obscure breadcrumbs.

05:32.724 --> 05:35.250
♪ ♪

05:45.662 --> 05:47.679
♪ ♪

05:53.579 --> 05:55.729
♪ ♪

06:03.589 --> 06:05.530
(gasps slowly)

06:11.613 --> 06:13.187
Coming up, dinner.

06:13.207 --> 06:16.208
But first, I turn my back
to a dangerous murderer.

06:17.102 --> 06:19.044
(regurgitates)

06:23.199 --> 06:26.259
(indistinct chatter)

06:28.204 --> 06:30.722
Oh, hey, Sarge. Your wife
called and said it was urgent.

06:30.949 --> 06:32.391
Oh, uh, okay.

06:32.618 --> 06:35.209
Yeah,
she sounded very not happy.

06:35.229 --> 06:36.953
You need to call her back ASAP.

06:36.972 --> 06:38.288
Got it, thanks.

06:38.306 --> 06:41.191
Starting to think
I did this guy a favor.

06:46.632 --> 06:47.647
(doorbell rings)

06:47.741 --> 06:50.742
It puts its finger
on the doorbell.

06:50.894 --> 06:52.393
We're looking for someone.

06:52.413 --> 06:53.637
Have you seen her?

06:53.805 --> 06:57.732
Oh, wait, is she
that great, big, huge, plump,

06:57.793 --> 07:01.235
very large, Rubenesque,
fat girl who went missing?

07:01.255 --> 07:02.829
Yes, she is rather heavy,

07:02.981 --> 07:05.072
and as you can see,
not particularly attractive.

07:05.167 --> 07:06.925
We've had reports
that her personality

07:07.076 --> 07:08.334
is quite grating as well.

07:08.503 --> 07:11.012
MEG (distant):
I can still hear you guys!

07:15.010 --> 07:17.227
(panting)

07:20.666 --> 07:22.149
(door creaks)

07:23.001 --> 07:25.502
(goggles whirring)

07:25.595 --> 07:28.004
(panting)

07:28.023 --> 07:29.406
(gasps)

07:30.642 --> 07:33.100
I'm not loving
this night vision setting.

07:33.120 --> 07:36.955
Maybe I should try
<i> Night at the Roxbury</i> vision.

07:37.182 --> 07:39.349
(Haddaway's "What Is Love?"
playing)

07:39.442 --> 07:41.418
♪ ♪

07:42.796 --> 07:45.630
-You? Me? You?
-♪<i> What is love?</i> ♪
-(screams)

07:47.225 --> 07:51.052
It puts the bullet
in the fat guy.

07:54.700 --> 07:57.142
And, for having
successfully scaled a cargo net

07:57.369 --> 08:00.553
and connecting two note cards
with a piece of red string,

08:00.706 --> 08:05.466
Clarice Starling, you are now
officially a lady FBI.

08:05.560 --> 08:08.111
(applause)

08:09.881 --> 08:11.990
(phone ringing)

08:15.311 --> 08:16.811
You should probably answer that.

08:16.905 --> 08:19.414
I mean, you're the closest thing
to a secretary in here.

08:20.408 --> 08:21.983
Ugh.

08:22.077 --> 08:25.578
Hello, FBI.
This is Clarice speaking.

08:25.672 --> 08:27.005
Hello, Clarice.

08:27.156 --> 08:29.566
I just wanted to let you know
that I respect you,

08:29.659 --> 08:32.118
and how important it is
that you're a woman.

08:32.270 --> 08:34.237
Thank you for saying so, Doctor.

08:34.406 --> 08:35.572
'Cause if you were a man,

08:35.665 --> 08:37.682
I would definitely be captured
or dead by now.

08:37.834 --> 08:40.426
-Oh, I...
-Like if you're Clint Eastwood,
I'm dead.

08:40.521 --> 08:43.170
-Harrison Ford? Dead.
-Well, Doctor,
I've really got...

08:43.265 --> 08:45.415
You know, I'm not betting
against the<i> Twin Peaks</i> guy--

08:45.433 --> 08:46.933
what's his name?
Creepy white guy.

08:47.085 --> 08:49.102
-Kyle MacLachlan.
-Kyle MacLachlan, right.

08:49.196 --> 08:50.362
How do I keep forgetting that?

08:50.531 --> 08:53.106
It's like in my top five
dude names. I have a list.

08:53.200 --> 08:55.683
-Dr. Lecter,
I really have to go.
-So do I.

08:55.777 --> 08:57.994
♪ ♪

08:59.355 --> 09:02.189
I'm having an old friend
for dinner.

09:02.209 --> 09:04.042
Y-You're gonna eat a friend?

09:04.119 --> 09:05.377
That was kind of
supposed to be the last line,

09:05.604 --> 09:06.770
and you ruined it.

09:06.863 --> 09:08.863
I'm gonna say it again
and then hang up quickly.

09:08.990 --> 09:10.048
(clears throat)

09:10.199 --> 09:12.366
I'm having an old friend
for dinner.

09:12.460 --> 09:14.427
<i> -What?!</i>
-Oh, my God, this bitch.

09:18.892 --> 09:20.708
♪ ♪

09:20.727 --> 09:22.561
<i> PETER:</i>
<i> My name is...</i>

09:22.788 --> 09:25.471
<i>whatever Kevin Spacey's name was</i>
<i> in this movie.</i>

09:25.624 --> 09:27.381
<i> I bet you think</i>
<i> behind that door is</i>

09:27.401 --> 09:29.309
<i> a happy,</i>
<i> all-American family.</i>

09:29.461 --> 09:30.068
<i> Nope.</i>

09:30.219 --> 09:31.311
<i> Just me in the shower</i>

09:31.405 --> 09:33.554
<i> with Johnson & Johnson</i>
<i> and Johnson.</i>

09:33.648 --> 09:35.481
<i> There were some tears.</i>

09:35.576 --> 09:37.817
<i> That's my wife out there,</i>
<i> cutting roses.</i>

09:37.911 --> 09:40.620
<i> Oh, just a heads-up,</i>
<i>there's a ton of roses in this.</i>

09:40.730 --> 09:43.230
<i> I guess they're supposed to</i>
<i> mean something. (sighs)</i>

09:43.325 --> 09:44.749
<i>You know, when I agreed to this,</i>

09:44.901 --> 09:46.918
<i> I 100% thought it was</i>
American Pie.

09:47.070 --> 09:49.145
<i> Always read the second word</i>
<i> of the title</i>

09:49.164 --> 09:50.313
<i> before you sign something.</i>

09:50.406 --> 09:53.091
Oh, hi, Carolyn.
We're your gay neighbors.

09:53.318 --> 09:55.076
That's right,
and we're the only happy people

09:55.095 --> 09:56.428
in the entire film.

09:56.579 --> 09:58.079
<i> PETER:</i>
<i> Oh, that's the other thing.</i>

09:58.098 --> 09:59.489
<i> This movie really</i>
<i> wants you to know</i>

09:59.582 --> 10:02.158
<i> that traditional families are</i>
<i> the messed-up ones.</i>

10:02.251 --> 10:03.751
<i> If you don't want</i>
<i> two hours of that,</i>

10:03.829 --> 10:05.103
<i> go turn on</i> The Matrix.

10:05.296 --> 10:06.771
<i> Aw, why aren't we doing that?</i>

10:06.923 --> 10:08.164
Have a great day,

10:08.183 --> 10:10.667
two-dimensional '90s
gay neighbors!

10:10.669 --> 10:13.853
-Who are both named Jim.
-Right, who are both named Jim.

10:14.931 --> 10:17.282
-Good morning, my darling.
-Hello, my love.

10:17.433 --> 10:19.784
<i> PETER: Keep in mind</i>
<i> that 9/11 hasn't happened yet.</i>

10:19.936 --> 10:21.769
<i> So a strained family dynamic</i>

10:21.788 --> 10:23.771
<i> is still the most</i>
<i> dramatic thing there is.</i>

10:23.865 --> 10:27.792
Wow, what a beautiful,
fully heterosexual neighborhood.

10:27.944 --> 10:30.854
Yeah, no.
What's up is down here, bro.

10:30.872 --> 10:33.039
Oh, hi, you must be
our new neighbors.

10:33.133 --> 10:34.949
I'm Carolyn Burnham,

10:35.043 --> 10:37.952
RE/MAX's top crying realtor
in the area.

10:38.004 --> 10:39.804
Uh, thanks,
but we just bought a house,

10:40.031 --> 10:41.714
so we don't really need
a realtor.

10:41.867 --> 10:44.476
(crying)

10:44.627 --> 10:46.719
-You don't?
-S-Sorry.

10:46.872 --> 10:48.480
It's okay. You know what?

10:48.631 --> 10:49.648
We'll buy another one.

10:49.875 --> 10:52.041
(chuckles):
Oh, great. Great.

10:52.135 --> 10:54.727
Oh, looks like
your son and my daughter

10:54.821 --> 10:56.137
are getting to know each other.

10:56.231 --> 10:59.491
Check out this video I took
of a plastic bag.

10:59.642 --> 11:01.618
♪ ♪

11:03.054 --> 11:04.737
I'm thinking about
sending it in

11:04.831 --> 11:07.056
to<i> America's Funniest</i>
<i> Home Videos.</i>

11:07.075 --> 11:08.983
Really? Do you think
it's funny enough?

11:09.002 --> 11:11.911
I don't know.
I just want to spend $2,000

11:12.005 --> 11:15.748
flying to Los Angeles
to maybe win $1,000.

11:15.901 --> 11:18.009
(crowd cheering inside)

11:20.088 --> 11:21.680
-(whistle blows)
<i> -ANNOUNCER: That's halftime.</i>

11:21.907 --> 11:24.240
<i> And now, please welcome</i>
<i> the Suburbia High School</i>

11:24.259 --> 11:27.243
<i> cheer quad,</i>
<i> the Dockers Zipper Pushers.</i>

11:27.262 --> 11:29.412
(upbeat music plays)

11:29.431 --> 11:31.439
♪ ♪

11:39.774 --> 11:41.682
Who is that?

11:41.851 --> 11:43.684
(sultry music plays)

11:43.853 --> 11:47.330
♪ ♪

11:55.198 --> 11:57.106
Ah! Ah, damn it! Ah, stop. Stop.

11:57.125 --> 12:00.142
I have seasonal allergies, guys.
(sneezes)

12:00.144 --> 12:02.278
-(upbeat music resumes)
<i> -ANNOUNCER: All right.</i>

12:02.371 --> 12:03.537
<i> Now the marching band to play</i>

12:03.615 --> 12:05.798
<i> the Suburbia High School</i>
<i> fight song.</i>

12:05.892 --> 12:08.101
(playing "Two Princes"
by Spin Doctors)

12:10.897 --> 12:12.472
Geez, again with this song?

12:12.624 --> 12:14.974
Shut up and kiss me,
other gay Jim.

12:15.126 --> 12:17.402
(both moaning)

12:17.553 --> 12:20.071
Oh, no. No.

12:20.223 --> 12:22.073
I'm very against that.

12:22.150 --> 12:24.133
Remember that for later.

12:24.135 --> 12:25.577
<i> PETER:</i>
<i> The next day, I quit my job</i>

12:25.804 --> 12:28.137
<i> and was in no way</i>
<i> run out of the industry</i>

12:28.231 --> 12:29.973
<i> for groping a busboy</i>
<i> in Nantucket.</i>

12:29.991 --> 12:32.008
It was a joke.
I was razzing the guy.

12:32.010 --> 12:33.400
Come on.

12:33.420 --> 12:34.902
(sizzling)

12:34.921 --> 12:38.481
<i>I got a new job at a fake movie</i>
<i> fast food restaurant.</i>

12:38.500 --> 12:41.985
<i> God, why are movies so bad</i>
<i> at naming restaurants?</i>

12:42.003 --> 12:44.962
Welcome to Mr. Smiley's
BurgerTownVilleLand.

12:45.098 --> 12:46.914
Would you like to try
a Large McIntyre?

12:46.933 --> 12:50.584
<i> LOIS:</i>
<i> Yes, my lover and I will each</i>
<i> have adultery burgers.</i>

12:50.662 --> 12:52.437
Second window.

12:52.588 --> 12:54.105
(moaning)

12:55.108 --> 12:58.443
-Two adultery burgers.
-(gasps) Lester!

12:58.670 --> 13:00.928
(chuckles nervously) Listen,
let's not make a big scene here.

13:01.022 --> 13:02.280
We can talk about this
when we get...

13:02.431 --> 13:07.452
<i> You</i> don't get to tell<i> me</i>
what to do anymore.

13:08.696 --> 13:10.288
We need more ketchup.

13:10.439 --> 13:13.199
All right, there are some things
you can tell me to do.

13:13.368 --> 13:15.868
<i> After that, I started</i>
<i> lifting weights in my garage.</i>

13:16.021 --> 13:17.370
<i> But I lost track of a spider</i>

13:17.522 --> 13:19.113
<i> that crawled</i>
<i> behind the heavy ones,</i>

13:19.132 --> 13:21.800
<i> so I had to use the dainty</i>
<i> weights ladies walk with.</i>

13:21.909 --> 13:23.693
Oh, hey. You got those drugs?

13:23.711 --> 13:24.877
Yep, right here.

13:25.030 --> 13:26.638
Oh, my God.

13:26.789 --> 13:29.048
Look at that plastic bag.

13:29.200 --> 13:31.050
So beautiful.

13:31.202 --> 13:33.478
Do you do a lot of the drugs
yourself?

13:33.629 --> 13:34.979
I do, yes.

13:35.131 --> 13:36.797
Okay, let me just get
on my knees

13:36.817 --> 13:40.634
and roll a joint at crotch level
like all drug dealers do.

13:40.654 --> 13:43.062
Great, and I'll just lean back,
away from the drugs

13:43.139 --> 13:45.490
like all drug users do.

13:47.886 --> 13:49.327
What the hell?

13:49.496 --> 13:51.145
Am I seeing
what I think I'm seeing?

13:51.164 --> 13:52.664
Help me out here, Mr. Furley.

13:52.891 --> 13:55.058
How did this thing win an Oscar?

13:55.076 --> 13:57.502
It's basically<i> Austin Powers.</i>

13:57.653 --> 14:00.505
♪ ♪

14:00.656 --> 14:02.340
Yo, yo, check this out.

14:02.491 --> 14:05.159
What if, like, Kramer is just

14:05.253 --> 14:07.828
a figment of Jerry's
imagination?

14:07.848 --> 14:11.165
-Wow. Yeah.
-'Cause think about it.

14:11.259 --> 14:15.595
We-we never see him interacting
with anyone else.

14:15.747 --> 14:17.021
Yeah.

14:17.173 --> 14:21.084
Well-well, wait. I mean...
(stammers) we-we do.

14:21.102 --> 14:24.178
(chuckles):
Oh, boy, am I glad you're here.

14:24.272 --> 14:27.014
I don't think I like
what I saw earlier.

14:27.033 --> 14:28.349
Oh, was it<i> The Phantom Menace,</i>

14:28.368 --> 14:29.775
which also came out
this same year?

14:29.928 --> 14:31.018
Yeah, what a mess.

14:31.112 --> 14:34.430
Ricky, go on home.
I need to talk to Lester.

14:34.599 --> 14:36.282
Aw, I don't want to.

14:36.434 --> 14:38.601
(singsongy):
There's plastic bags.

14:38.694 --> 14:40.361
(gasps) There are?

14:41.456 --> 14:44.957
Hey, you know how there's
two things we know for sure?

14:45.051 --> 14:47.793
We'll always be able to
bring box cutters on planes,

14:47.888 --> 14:50.446
-and I'm heterosexual?
-Yeah, of course.

14:50.448 --> 14:53.707
Well, turns out only one of
those things is true.

14:53.727 --> 14:55.376
Mm...

14:55.470 --> 14:57.470
Look, I think I gave you
the wrong idea

14:57.564 --> 15:00.806
with these pink weights and
pantomiming oral with your son.

15:00.975 --> 15:02.901
-I'm straight.
-I'm so sorry!

15:03.052 --> 15:05.628
I got to go start a megachurch!

15:05.797 --> 15:07.447
Eh, seems right.

15:09.150 --> 15:11.409
Oh, hey,
what are you doing here?

15:11.560 --> 15:12.652
I have a flight tomorrow,

15:12.804 --> 15:15.154
and Jane said I could borrow
your box cutter.

15:15.306 --> 15:17.974
Man, I love cutting boxes
on planes.

15:17.992 --> 15:21.827
And also-- and this is kind of
embarrassing and unearned--

15:21.980 --> 15:26.315
but I think you're sexy,
and I want to have sex with you.

15:26.334 --> 15:28.242
Ah, sweet! Let's do this!

15:28.261 --> 15:31.504
I should let you know,
I'm a virgin.

15:31.598 --> 15:33.005
Not a deal-breaker.

15:33.158 --> 15:34.490
And I should let you know

15:34.509 --> 15:37.084
I'm Chris Hansen
from<i> To Catch a Predator.</i>

15:37.103 --> 15:38.752
Aw, crap. Somebody shoot me.

15:38.846 --> 15:40.104
(gunshot)

15:42.776 --> 15:44.016
Sorry, I didn't mean to...

15:44.169 --> 15:46.018
Whoa, you're Chris Hansen!

15:46.171 --> 15:49.388
Hey, what do you do with all
the leftover pedophile pizza?

15:49.449 --> 15:51.691
<i> PETER:</i>
<i>Well, that was</i> American Beauty.

15:51.843 --> 15:53.117
<i> See you at the Oscars.</i>

15:53.269 --> 15:54.694
<i> I'll be there with my mom.</i>

15:54.770 --> 15:57.497
<i> That's not a big, obvious sign</i>
<i> of something, right?</i>

16:02.020 --> 16:04.128
♪ ♪

16:12.046 --> 16:14.472
-How's work, Ralph?
-It's a breeze.

16:14.623 --> 16:16.365
(both laughing)

16:16.459 --> 16:19.060
-Give my best to Judy.
-Will do.

16:25.210 --> 16:28.044
Hi, my name's Forrest.

16:28.062 --> 16:29.378
Forrest Gump.

16:29.472 --> 16:31.972
Would it be okay
if I sugarcoat race relations

16:32.050 --> 16:34.550
in the South for
the next two and a half hours?

16:34.569 --> 16:37.829
Honey, I'm a Black woman
in a '90s Hollywood movie,

16:37.980 --> 16:40.223
-that's what I'm here for.
-Great.

16:40.316 --> 16:43.835
My mama always said life was
like a box of Good & Plenty:

16:43.986 --> 16:46.170
most people just throw it away.

16:46.397 --> 16:48.748
<i> One day on the bus to school,</i>

16:48.900 --> 16:50.657
<i> I met Jenny.</i>

16:50.677 --> 16:53.261
<i> She was the love of my life.</i>

16:55.015 --> 16:57.590
Hey, look, it's a guy
with nonstandard legs.

16:57.684 --> 17:00.560
Let's bully and
throw rocks at him and not me.

17:01.596 --> 17:04.046
Run, Forrest, run!

17:04.932 --> 17:06.340
<i> PETER:</i>
<i> And in a magical moment</i>

17:06.509 --> 17:09.193
<i> whose explanation</i>
<i> I assume was cut for time,</i>

17:09.345 --> 17:12.255
<i>I could suddenly run very fast.</i>

17:12.348 --> 17:13.939
<i> But I happened to do it</i>

17:14.092 --> 17:16.850
<i> in front of the meanest</i>
<i> lifeguard in Alabama.</i>

17:16.928 --> 17:20.279
-No running!
-It's for a movie. God.

17:20.431 --> 17:22.114
-(cheering)
<i> -I was such a fast runner,</i>

17:22.283 --> 17:25.192
<i> I went on to play</i>
<i> college movie football,</i>

17:25.211 --> 17:29.297
<i> where all the tacklers dive</i>
<i> two feet behind you and miss.</i>

17:31.459 --> 17:32.958
After I graduated,

17:33.053 --> 17:35.945
I joined the Army
and got shipped off to war.

17:35.963 --> 17:39.465
<i> Vietnam is where I met</i>
<i> my best friend, Bubba,</i>

17:39.617 --> 17:42.968
<i> who really wanted to have</i>
<i> his own squid fishing boat.</i>

17:43.121 --> 17:45.304
<i> In fact, he knew just about</i>

17:45.456 --> 17:47.231
<i> everything you could do</i>
<i> with a squid.</i>

17:47.383 --> 17:49.984
Well, there's calamari...

17:51.887 --> 17:53.629
That's about it.

17:53.722 --> 17:56.199
Ambush! (screaming)

17:57.151 --> 17:59.744
Oh, my God, Lieutenant Dan!

18:01.155 --> 18:03.730
Damn it, save yourself, Gump.

18:03.808 --> 18:06.475
-Leave me here.
-All right.

18:06.569 --> 18:07.643
(explosion)

18:07.662 --> 18:09.403
<i> Bubba was also shot.</i>

18:09.422 --> 18:12.315
<i> And as always happens</i>
<i> when a soldier dies,</i>

18:12.333 --> 18:14.333
<i> we discussed business ideas.</i>

18:14.485 --> 18:17.503
(weakly):
I'm dying, Forrest.

18:17.597 --> 18:20.264
I want you to buy
a squid boat in my honor.

18:20.416 --> 18:23.601
How about a gym
exclusively for big white women?

18:23.828 --> 18:27.271
-There could be machines that...
-Whoa, whoa, whoa.

18:27.423 --> 18:30.775
You had me at "big white women."

18:30.926 --> 18:32.443
(exhales)

18:32.595 --> 18:35.113
-(chanting)
<i>-After I got home from Vietnam,</i>

18:35.340 --> 18:38.007
<i> I got to speak</i>
<i> at a generic protest.</i>

18:38.025 --> 18:41.026
There's only one thing
to say about Vietnam:

18:41.195 --> 18:44.271
I had this awesome red stuff
on all my food.

18:44.365 --> 18:46.031
I don't 'member
what it's called.

18:46.126 --> 18:48.517
It's not hot sauce,
but it's not ketchup.

18:48.611 --> 18:51.295
I think it's got
a rooster on the label.

18:51.447 --> 18:52.630
Forrest!

18:54.041 --> 18:56.217
(gasps) Jenny!

18:57.044 --> 18:58.210
Aah! Son of a bitch!

18:58.304 --> 19:01.622
See, guys?
This is why no running.

19:01.641 --> 19:04.033
<i> PETER:</i>
<i> And then-- I know,</i>
<i> it's still not over yet--</i>

19:04.126 --> 19:06.369
<i> I bought a squid boat.</i>

19:06.387 --> 19:08.704
<i> Lieutenant Dan was also</i>
<i> working with me.</i>

19:08.723 --> 19:11.040
<i> And you know</i>
<i> who's super helpful on a boat</i>

19:11.058 --> 19:13.058
<i> that's constantly rocking</i>
<i> in the water?</i>

19:13.211 --> 19:14.710
<i> A wheelchair guy.</i>

19:14.729 --> 19:16.821
Hey, Forrest, I got our lunches.

19:16.898 --> 19:20.158
-(waves crashing)
-(screams)

19:22.829 --> 19:24.887
So after I was rich,

19:24.906 --> 19:28.106
Jenny came back
and had sex with me one time.

19:28.259 --> 19:30.409
Wow, that was great.

19:30.561 --> 19:33.320
Sorry I was naming presidents
during.

19:33.398 --> 19:35.080
So, we getting married or what?

19:35.233 --> 19:37.967
You don't want to marry me,
Forrest.

19:38.845 --> 19:40.236
Yeah, you're right.

19:40.254 --> 19:42.346
Okay, well, have a good night.

19:42.498 --> 19:45.090
<i> And then,</i>
<i> shockingly late in the movie,</i>

19:45.167 --> 19:47.018
<i> I started running again.</i>

19:47.094 --> 19:49.078
<i> Like, across the country.</i>

19:49.096 --> 19:50.262
<i> Several times.</i>

19:50.356 --> 19:51.931
<i> The whole sequence</i>
<i> is a full eight minutes.</i>

19:52.083 --> 19:54.174
<i> I mean, sometimes this whole</i>
<i>movie feels like it was written</i>

19:54.194 --> 19:56.419
<i> by a seven-year-old</i>
<i> who just ate a bunch of candy.</i>

19:56.437 --> 19:58.512
<i> But I checked,</i>
<i> it's just a regular guy.</i>

19:58.531 --> 20:00.272
<i> Anyway,</i>
<i> at least we were finally</i>

20:00.366 --> 20:02.700
<i> to the time</i>
<i> in our nation's history</i>

20:02.851 --> 20:04.093
<i> when I could listen to this.</i>

20:04.186 --> 20:07.622
♪<i> Princes,</i>
<i> princes who adore you.</i> ♪

20:10.543 --> 20:12.126
(knocking)

20:12.937 --> 20:14.027
Forrest!

20:14.214 --> 20:17.531
I brought you chocolates
picked over by strangers.

20:17.625 --> 20:19.124
Forrest, I'm sick.

20:19.277 --> 20:22.127
-Sick? With what?
-(whispers indistinctly)

20:22.222 --> 20:24.204
Oh, I did a movie
about that once.

20:24.298 --> 20:26.057
It's called<i> Splash.</i>

20:26.208 --> 20:28.951
No, Forrest.
(whispers indistinctly)

20:28.970 --> 20:31.470
Oh, I thought you said mermaids.

20:31.564 --> 20:34.065
But I did a movie about
your thing, too.

20:34.216 --> 20:35.882
But that's not all.

20:35.960 --> 20:37.309
I want you to meet my son.

20:37.462 --> 20:39.904
Six hours in makeup. One line.

20:40.131 --> 20:41.647
You're his father.

20:41.741 --> 20:43.724
Father?

20:43.801 --> 20:46.135
Is he... like me?

20:46.228 --> 20:47.486
Uhp, you died.

20:47.638 --> 20:49.305
And... feather!

20:49.323 --> 20:51.332
